Input.threadtitle: PS2 Problem 1 : Solution Set. Can we not finish one cycle early for Full Bypassing
Input.posts:
Looking at the Solution set for PS2, Problem 1. If we have a Full bypass as suggested in the question,can not the Y1 stage of the Load Instruction ( LW R10, 0(R6) ) forward the data to the X0 stage for the Add instruction ( ADD R6, R9, R10 \xA0? \xA0 If that would be the case then the last 2 Instructions in the pipeline diagram would finish one cycle early. \xA0 \xA0 ADD R6, R9, R10 \xA0 \xA0F D X0 X1 W \xA0 ADD R8, R10, R11 \xA0F F \xA0D \xA0X0 X1 W \xA0 Am I missing something? \xA0If such is bypass is either not implemented or cannot be done, then we would have the pipeline as shown in the Solution set.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
I don't think the problem is due to bypassing, more to do with in-order execution. \xA0Take a look at the two LD instruction to R15. \xA0The first LD instruction (LW R15, 4(R6)) is issued down the pipe, and the next LD instruction (LW R15, 4(R15)) needs the result of the first load before it can issue. \xA0Thus, the second load waits for the first load to enter the Y1 stage before it issues down the Y pipe. \xA0Now, the ADD following the second load (ADD R6, R9, R10) could issue as soon as it enters the decode stage, as all of its operands are ready, however must stall due to the previous LD instruction. \xA0If it were to issue as soon as it enters the decode stage, it would be issuing the ADD out-of-order with respect to the LD and the ADD would commit before the previous LD, which implies out-of-order execution. \xA0Since the problem states the processor is in-order, it cannot issue or execute instructions out-of-order. \xA0Thus, the LD is causing the extra latency.

I don't think the problem is due to bypassing, more to do with in-order execution. \xA0Take a look at the two LD instruction to R15. \xA0The first LD instruction (LW R15, 4(R6)) is issued down the pipe, and the next LD instruction (LW R15, 4(R15)) needs the result of the first load before it can issue. \xA0Thus, the second load waits for the first load to enter the Y1 stage before it issues down the Y pipe. \xA0Now, the ADD following the second load (ADD R6, R9, R10) could issue as soon as it enters the decode stage, as all of its operands are ready, however must stall due to the previous LD instruction. \xA0If it were to issue as soon as it enters the decode stage, it would be issuing the ADD out-of-order with respect to the LD and the ADD would commit before the previous LD, which implies out-of-order execution. \xA0Since the problem states the processor is in-order, it cannot issue or execute instructions out-of-order. \xA0Thus, the LD is causing the extra latency.

Input.threadtitle: P1 - 3 - 'register read and a write in the same clock cycle forwards through the register file'
Input.posts:
\xA0'Register read and a write in the same clock cycle forwards through the register file' - what does this mean? Does it mean that an instruction which reads a register can do the Decode phase while another instruction which writes the same register does the Writeback phase? Or something else?
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Yes, this means if an instruction in the writeback stage is writing to the same register that is being read by an instruction in the decode stage, the register file will forward the value being written to the read. Thus, the instruction reading the register in the decode stage will see the new value being written back and not the value stored in the register before the write. \xA0Extra logic in the register file is actually required to detect this case and forward the value. \xA0If this logic was not present, the read could possibly see the old value since the clock period would have to be long enough to include the propagation delay of the write followed by the propagation delay of the read in order to see the new value. \xA0It would likely not be the case that the clock period is long enough for this to occur, and, thus, the read would see the old value.\xA0

Input.posts:
I guess I need to determine the average CPI for the loads/stores. I am assuming that the cache hit/miss rates dictate the CPI these two instructions are going to have. However, I can't convert the cycles it takes to access the cache to the effective clock cycles the instructions use. For example, a load instruction goes through, fetch, decode and execute stages. When it comes to the memory stage, it will go query the cache.\xA0 If it's a hit, it will take 1 cycle and 120 cycles if it's a miss.\xA0 In light of all this, can I assume that a load instruction with a hit will take 1 cycle to complete while one that misses will take 120? Do I disregard the previous phases (f,d,e) the instruction went through before it queried the cache?
Upvotes:
1
For load/store instructions you have to assume that 60 % of them will take 1 clock cycle to execute, the rest, so 40 % will need 120 cc. These instructions represent 34 % of total number of executed instructions.
Upvotes:
0

Instructor's Post
Yes, you assume a load hit will take 1 cycle, and a load miss will take 120 cycles. \xA0We ignore the cycles used to fill the pipeline, and focus more on the throughput of the pipeline. You can use the percentages given to take a weighted average and obtain an average CPI for load instructions.
